Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows two coils of basketry. The upper side is flat, showing several finger imprints. About two thirds of the impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two seated figures at the top, facing each other, signs above their heads that are not recognisable anymore. Underneath a horizontal mr sign (N36) and other horizontal signs below that are only partly preserved and not identifiable anymore.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
